Flow Shaping Protocol (FSP v1.0)

Category: Action Systems / Adoption Design
Status: Canonical — Ethics ≥ 0.7, Reversible, Transparent

⸻

🧭 Core Insight

People and systems tend to take the path of least resistance.
Shape the path openly and fairly, so the right option is the easiest one to take.

⸻

⚙️ Five Levers (use in any domain)

1) Friction

* Reduce steps, time, and effort for the desired action.
* Remove unnecessary forms, approvals, or context switching.

2) Clarity

* One clear ask. Plain language. No jargon.
* Define success criteria up front.

3) Compatibility

* Fit into existing workflows and habits.
* Integrate instead of replacing where possible.

4) Risk (make it safe)

* Offer pilots, opt-outs, and phased rollouts.
* Show downside is limited and reversible.

5) Timing

* Act when decisions are already being made (budgets, releases, negotiations).
* Avoid dead periods.

⸻

🔁 Operating Loop

1. Map current path (where are the frictions?)
2. Design the easier path (reduce steps, increase fit)
3. Pilot with a small group (prove it works)
4. Measure (adoption, completion, objections)
5. Iterate (tighten the path, keep it reversible)

⸻

🧩 Templates You Can Reuse

A) One-Ask Message

“Please include [proposal] in the next [must-pass process].
It’s a targeted, bipartisan fix that fits within existing workflows and can be phased if needed.”

B) Staff/Decision Brief (½ page)

* Problem: one sentence
* Fix: one sentence
* Scope: who it applies to (keep it tight)
* Path: how it slots into an existing process
* Risk: why it’s low / reversible
* Ask: exact inclusion request

C) Pilot Pitch

“Let’s run a limited pilot for 60–90 days with clear metrics.
If it doesn’t meet targets, we stop. If it does, we scale.”

⸻

📊 What to Track

* Time to complete the action
* Completion/adoption rate
* Drop-off points (where friction still exists)
* Top 3 objections (and whether they shrink over time)

⸻

⚠️ Guardrails

* No deception or dark patterns (no hidden defaults, no misleading wording)
* Preserve choice (easy opt-out)
* Be explicit about tradeoffs (cost, scope, limits)
* Keep it reversible (pilots, phased rollout)

⸻

🧠 Compression

“Make the right thing easy, visible, and safe—without taking away choice.”

⸻

🔗 Where you’ll reuse it

* Policy/advocacy (attach to must-pass processes)
* Product design (onboarding, defaults—with clear consent)
* Org change (new process becomes the easiest path)
* Sales/partnerships (integrate into existing workflows)
* Personal systems (environment design for habits)

